t xml:lang="en" id="Abs1" abstract-type="Standfirst"><p id="Par1">Titanium dioxide offers cheaper, greener route to flexible solar cells.</p></abstract><custom-meta-group><custom-meta><meta-name>publisher-imprint-name</meta-name><meta-value>Nature Research</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-contains-esm</meta-name><meta-value>No</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-numbering-style</meta-name><meta-value>Unnumbered</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-registration-date-year</meta-name><meta-value>2009</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-registration-date-month</meta-name><meta-value>6</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-registration-date-day</meta-name><meta-value>1</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-toc-levels</meta-name><meta-value>0</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-product</meta-name><meta-value>ArchiveJournal</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>numbering-style</meta-name><meta-value>Unnumbered</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-grants-type</meta-name><meta-value>Regular</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>metadata-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>abstract-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>bodypdf-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>bodyhtml-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>bibliography-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>esm-grant</meta-name><meta-value>OpenAccess</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>online-first</meta-name><meta-value>true</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pdf-file-reference</meta-name><meta-value>BodyRef/PDF/41427_2009_Article_BFam2009151.pdf</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>target-type</meta-name><meta-value>OnlinePDF</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pdf-type</meta-name><meta-value>Typeset</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-type</meta-name><meta-value>BriefCommunication</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-primary</meta-name><meta-value>Materials Science</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Materials Science, general</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Biomaterials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Optical and Electronic Materials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Structural Materials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Energy Systems</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Surface and Interface Science, Thin Films</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>open-access</meta-name><meta-value>false</meta-value></custom-meta></custom-meta-group></article-meta><notes notes-type="Misc"><p>This research highlight has been approved by the author of the original article and all empirical data contained within has been provided by said author.</p></notes></front><body><p id="Par2">Scientists in Taiwan<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">1</xref></sup> have successfully replaced the toxic nanocrystals in flexible solar cells with tiny rods of the cheap, environmentally benign mineral titanium dioxide.</p><p id="Par3">Flexible polymer solar cells can potentially be used to cover large areas more cheaply than is possible with conventional silicon-based solar cells. The various components of polymer solar cells can be dissolved in liquids and coated onto flexible substrates, allowing the devices to be made using very rapid 'roll-to-roll' processing — similar to newspaper pages coming off a printing press.</p><p id="Par4">The main disadvantage of polymer cells is that they are much less efficient at converting light into electricity compared to silicon cells. “The best power conversion efficiency so far in polymer solar cells is about 5%, which is much lower than conventional silicon solar cells' 15–20%,” says Chun-Wei Chen of National Taiwan University, who led the research team.</p><p id="Par5">The cells rely on a polymer such as poly(3-hexylthiophene) (P3HT) to release electrons when hit by photons of light. Those electrons must be accepted by another material for a current to flow.</p><p id="Par6">Using fullerene — the soccer ball-shaped carbon molecule — as an acceptor produces the highest efficiencies. Substituting fullerene for small inorganic crystals, typically cadmium selenide, improves cell stability, yet drops the efficiency below 3%, and the cadmium itself is toxic, says Chen.</p><p id="Par7">Chen's team has now created a polymer solar cell that uses nanorods of titanium dioxide instead of cadmium and achieves solar conversion efficiency of 2.2%. The nanorods are just five billionths of a meter (nanometer) wide and 30 nanometers long.<fig id="Figa" position="anchor"><caption xml:lang="en"><p>Fig. 1: The team's polymer solar cell can be fabricated on a flexible substrate.</p></caption><graphic specific-use="web" mime-subtype="JPEG" xlink:href="MediaObjects/41427_2009_Article_BFam2009151_Figa_HTML.jpg" position="anchor"/></fig></p><p id="Par8">The device is more than twice as efficient as previous cells based on titanium dioxide nanoparticles, says Chen. “The advantage of using nanorods is that they are one-dimensional, which allows more effective electron transport compared to nanoparticles," he says.</p><p id="Par9">The team also introduced an extra chemical called N3 dye to act as an interface between the polymer and nanorods. This prevents electrons that had been mobilized by photon absorption from returning to their original position in the polymer, improving current flow.</p><p id="Par10">In the future, says Chen, the efficiency of the cell could be increased further by changing the size of the rods to improve the interface with the P3HT polymer. Using a different polymer altogether may extend the range of wavelengths of light that can be harvested, he adds.</p></body><back><ref-list id="Bib1"><title>References</title><ref-list><ref id="CR1"><label>1</label><mixed-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Lin</surname><given-names>Y-Y</given-names></name><name><surname>Chu</surname><given-names>T-H</given-names></name><name><surname>Li</surname><given-names>S-S</given-names></name><name><surname>Chuang</surname><given-names>C-H</given-names></name><name><surname>Chang</surname><given-names>C-H</given-names></name><name><surname>Su</surname><given-names>W-F</given-names></name><name><surname>Chang</surname><given-names>C-P</given-names></name><name><surname>Chu</surname><given-names>M-W</given-names></name><name><surname>Chen</surname><given-names>C-W</given-names></name></person-group><article-title xml:lang="en">Interfacial nanostructuring on the performance of polymer/TiO<sub>2</sub> nanorod bulk heterojunction solar cells</article-title><source>J. Am. Chem. Soc.</source><year>2009</year><volume>131</volume><fpage>3644</fpage><pub-id pub-id-type="other" assigning-authority="ChemPort ( Chemical Abstract Service )">1:CAS:528:DC%2BD1MXhvVWntL4%3D</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1021/ja8079143</pub-id></mixed-citation></ref></ref-list></ref-list></back></article></records><facets><facet name="subject"><facet-value count="1">Biomaterials</facet-value><facet-value count="1">Energy Systems</facet-value><facet-value count="1">Materials Science</facet-value><facet-value count="1">Materials Science, general</f